You should **prefer `reduce()` over `map()` when your problem is not a simple one‑to‑one transformation**, but instead requires **accumulating, combining, or producing a different shape of data**.

Below is a **clear decision guide**, with **examples that interviewers expect**.

***

## ✅ Core Rule (Memorize This)

> **Use `reduce` when you must compress multiple values into one result or avoid multiple array iterations.**

***

## ✅ When `map` is the WRONG Choice

### ❌ `map` limitations

*   Always returns an array
*   Output length === input length
*   Cannot naturally:
    *   Sum values
    *   Group data
    *   Build objects
    *   Count occurrences

If your output is **not an array of the same length**, `map` is not ideal.

***

## ✅ When to Prefer `reduce()` ✅

### 1️⃣ When you need a **single value** (sum, average, max, min)

```js
const nums = [10, 20, 30];

const sum = nums.reduce((acc, n) => acc + n, 0);
```

❌ `map` cannot do this  
✅ `reduce` is made for it

***

### 2️⃣ When you need to **build an object**

#### ✅ Example: Count occurrences

```js
const fruits = ["apple", "banana", "apple"];

const count = fruits.reduce((acc, fruit) => {
  acc[fruit] = (acc[fruit] || 0) + 1;
  return acc;
}, {});
```

✅ Output:

```js
{ apple: 2, banana: 1 }
```

❌ `map` cannot produce this result meaningfully

***

### 3️⃣ When you need to **group data**

✅ Very common in interviews & real apps

```js
const users = [
  { name: "A", role: "admin" },
  { name: "B", role: "user" },
  { name: "C", role: "admin" }
];

const grouped = users.reduce((acc, user) => {
  acc[user.role] = acc[user.role] || [];
  acc[user.role].push(user);
  return acc;
}, {});
```

✅ Output:

```js
{
  admin: [{...}, {...}],
  user: [{...}]
}
```

***

### 4️⃣ When replacing **map + filter combination** for performance

#### ❌ Multiple loops

```js
const result = users
  .filter(u => u.active)
  .map(u => u.name);
```

#### ✅ Single loop with `reduce`

```js
const result = users.reduce((acc, u) => {
  if (u.active) acc.push(u.name);
  return acc;
}, []);
```

✅ One iteration instead of two  
✅ Useful for **large datasets (1 lakh records)**

***

### 5️⃣ When the output shape is **unknown in advance**

✅ Object, array, number, string — all possible

```js
const state = actions.reduce((acc, action) => {
  return reducer(acc, action);
}, initialState);
```

➡️ This is literally how **Redux reducers** work.

***

### 6️⃣ When implementing **custom logic or aggregation**

```js
const cart = [
  { price: 100, qty: 2 },
  { price: 200, qty: 1 }
];

const total = cart.reduce(
  (sum, item) => sum + item.price * item.qty,
  0
);
```

✅ Clean  
✅ Expressive  
✅ Impossible with `map` alone

***

## ✅ When NOT to Prefer `reduce()` ❌

### ❌ Simple transformations

```js
arr.map(x => x * 2); // ✅ map is better
```

### ❌ Simple rendering in React

```jsx
items.map(item => <Item key={item.id} />); // ✅ map
```

⚠️ Using `reduce` here hurts readability.

***

## ✅ Decision Table (Interview Gold)

| Scenario               | Prefer     |
| ---------------------- | ---------- |
| Transform each element | `map` ✅    |
| Remove/select items    | `filter` ✅ |
| Sum / aggregate values | `reduce` ✅ |
| Build object           | `reduce` ✅ |
| Group data             | `reduce` ✅ |
| Replace map + filter   | `reduce` ✅ |
| React rendering        | `map` ✅    |

***

## ✅ One‑Line Interview Answer ⭐

> **Prefer `reduce` over `map` when you need to derive a single value, build a new data structure, or combine multiple operations into one iteration.**

***

## ✅ Simpler Rule to Remember

    Same number of items → map
    Fewer items → filter
    Different shape or single value → reduce

***

## ✅ Real‑World Insight (Senior‑Level)

*   `reduce` is **more powerful but less readable**
*   Use it **only when it adds value**
*   In React & teams → **clarity > cleverness**

